usiness man\nager of tbe Star.\nWhen John and Gardner\nCowles purchased the newt\npaper in 1905. Mr. Thompson\nstayed on to play a leading role\nj in building the property into\none of the largest publishing\nI ventures in the Midwest.\nHe was given the title pub\nllsher emeritus on his retire\nment in 1949. Survivors include\nhis widow, a son and two\ndaughter*.\nThomas Kilpatrick,\nr Printer 40 Years\nThomas Kilpatrick. 90. a re\n-1 tired printer -who worked at\nthe Bureau of Engraving and\nf Printing more than 40 years,\ndied yesterday at his home.\n4946 Butterworth place N.W.\nMr. Kilpatrick had lived in\nWashington since 1902. He\nretired in 1946. He was a com\nmunicant of the Westmoreland\nt Congregational Church.\nHe is survived by his widow.\nMrs. Sarah Elisabeth Kllpat\nt rfck of the home address: s\ndaughter. Mr*. Walter Bovard\nof Ormond Beach. Fla.: a sis\nter. Mrs. Martha Paul of Phil\nadelphia. and two granddaugh\nters.\nServices will be st 2p m. to\nmorrow at the Hines funeral\nhome, 2901 Fourteenth street\nN.W. Burial will be in Rock\nj Creek Cemetery.\nWilliam M. Early, Jr.,\nVirginia Banker\nORANGE. Va.. April 18\n\u2014William M. Early. Jr, presi\ndent of the National Bank of\nOrange and former president\n'of the Virginia Bankers Asso\nciation, died of a heart ailment\nhere yesterday.\nMr Early. 56, had heaped\nthe local bank the last 12\nyears. Earlier he had been as\nsociated with the Bank of\nj Salem.\ni. Surviving are his wife, a\ndaughter, two sisters and a\nbrother.\ni Funeral services are to be\nheld tomorrow at St. Thomas'\n3 Episcopal Church here. a\ni,\nDr. Albert Jump\na BRIDGETON, N. J, April 18\n(Ah.\u2014Dr. Albert B. Jump. 49,\na president of the Medical Society\nr of New Jersey, died today. He\nwas a graduate of Johns Hop\nr kins University and the Univer\nsity of Maryland Medical I\nSchool.\nDISTRICT TESTS AND BANISHES\nTOY MISSILE PRICED AT $4.98\n5 M\nThe latest in American Ingenuity\u2014a Bleek 84.99 toy j\nballistic missile\u2014received critical Inspection from District i\ni officials yesterday at test firings outside the Municipal\nCourt House.\nThe projectile, which soared 200 feet. Is powered by a\ncombination of citric acid and bicarbonate of aoda.\naccording to Deputy Fire Marshal Hugh A. Oroves.\nAlthough the marshal was satisfied that the plastic and\n3 \u201calpha-one\u201d is not inflammable. Assistant Corporation i\nCounsel Clark King and Police Inspector Thomas Ras- h\nj mussen concluded the missile Is too dangerous for\njuveniles.\nThe officials noted that the District code Is sufficiently\n'J up to date to provide that It is Illegal to give, lend, sell,\nrent or transfer \"a dangerous missile\u201d or \"projectile\" to\nanyone under 18\nThe toy. manufactured in Richmond, was withdrawn\nfrom sale at two downtown department stores at tha\nrequest of the police, who saw It advertsed in tha\ni newspapers.\nMr. King noted that the missile could be dangerous\nj' If fired horizontally or if a metal object was substituted\nSlichter Would Limit\nTax Cut to Excises\nProf. Sumner H. Slichter,\nHarvard University economist,\ntold the Senate Finance Con\nmittee today any tax cut at:\nthla time should ba conflnad te\na temporary reducUon In exeiae\nlevies on foods and services\nHla reason for the racom-1\nmendatlon was that a tax cut\nwould begin to cumulate the\neconomy at about tha same\ntime that spending program*\nalready pasaed by Congreaa\nwould begin to take effect.\n\"Consequently; unleu the\ntax out were quite mall, the\ncombined effect of the addl-\nUonal spending already author\nised and the tax eut could bo\nan overstlmulaUon of the econ\nomy,!\u2019 he said.\nh\nSecond Quarter Pick Up Seen\nProf. Slichter aald hli gueu\nu that the first phaaa of eco\nnomic recovery will atart in thla\nsecond quarter 0f'1668. He said\nIt will be followed by a second\nphase in the last half of the\nyear as Government spending\nconUnuei to grow and liquids- 1\ntlon of inventories will five way 1\nto accumulation of inventories.\nHe Mid housing also will begin\nto expand.\n\u201cSome time in 1959 busineu\noutlays on plant and equip\nment will start to rise.\u201d he con\ntinued. \u201cThat will mark a third\nTrain Robber j\nSuspect, Loot\nAre Seized\nBYDNEY. Nova Scotia, April\n11 (/pi\u2014 police searching for);\nthe masked gunman who\nrobbed an express train mall\ncar as It sped toward Sydney\nyesterday arrested a 41-year-\nold nun and announced recov- j\nery of the stolen goods today.\nThe man. who was not iden-\ntilled, was picked up shortly\nbefore dawn as he entered his\nuncle's house at Bucklaw, a\nfarming cpmmunity in Central!\nCapa Breton Island.\nThirty mounted police con\nstables with dogs had con-\nducted an all-night search of\nthe Orangedale area, where the:\ngunman apparently jumped off\nthe train after the robbery.\nRailway offlclah said soon after\nthe holdup that they believed\nthe gunman was a former em\nploye who knew mall car rou\ntine.\nArmed with a sawed-ofl\nshotgun, the robber boarded\nthe northbound train early\nyesterday at Port Hawkesbury,\nlocked mall clerks Lester Mac-\nKay and Gordon Mormsh inside\na washroom, and looted mail\nbags.\nHe escaped detection at\nOrangedale. the first stop after\nPort Hawkeabury, by tossing\nfour bags off the train tea\nwaiting mail carrier. Within\nthe next 30 miles he left the\nJ,\nll\nAdmiral Heads ,t\nMilitary Order\nANNAPOLIS. Md, April 18\n<#).\u2014A retired naval officer.\nRear Admiral A. Finley France\nof Annapolis, baa been elected\nSlate Commander of the Mili\ntary Order of World Wars.\nOther officers elected by\nmembers of the organization\nat their annual convention here\nare Brig. Gen. F. M. Harris of\nFort Meade, senior vice com\nmander: Col. John D. Slaugh\nter of Baltimore, junior vice\ncommander: Comdr. Chester\nE. Lewis of Annapolis, adju\ntant and treasurer: Brig. Oen.\nLanson Scribner of Easton.\nJudge advocate; Col. H. E.\nLeech of Fort Meade, surgeon,\nand Capt. Robert E. Miller of\nBaltimore historian and chap\nlain. All are retired.\nCapt. Miller, a former naval'\nchaplain, ia the retiring SUte\ncommander.\nBulova Left Wife\nOnly $25,000\nNEW YORK. April 18\nThe late watch magnate, Arde\nBulova. believed to have left\na multimlllion-dollar estate, cut\noff his estranged wife with a\n$25,000 bequest.\nl Mr. Bulova's will was filed\nfor probate yesterday in Sur\nrogate'a Court. The document\nleft half of his estate to the\nBulova Fund, Inc, a charitable\norganisation. The other half\nwent to two nephews and a\nniece.\nIn addition to leaving his\nwife Heana the $25,000. Bulova 1\ngranted her forgiveness of any:!\ndebts she owed him. They'\nwere not Itemized.\nMr. Bulova, 69. chairman\nof the board of Bulova Watch j'\nCo, died last March 18 in 1\nEncino. Calif, while his divorce\naction against the Romanian- 1\nborn Mrs. Bulova. In her 30s, 1\nwas pending in State Supreme; 1\nCourt here.\nphase In the recovery. A slow\nrise in spending on plant and\nequipment la preferable to a\nrapid rise. It should be under\nstood that the United Statti\ndoaa not have the instruments\nthrough which to combat a\nsudden upsurge In buying.\nNew-Madel Aalap\n\u201cFor example, after the poor\ncar year of 1956 the automo\nbile makers may come forward\nwith models that meet the peo\nple's fancy, and small econom\nical can may become the rage.\nWe could have In about 1960 or\n1961 a rush to buy can that\nwould be quite as disturbing as\nthe 7.2-mllllon car year of 1955.\u201d\nThe wltnees Mid there is no\nquick and early eolutlon to the\nproblem of wage* rising faster\nthan productivity. But he sug\ngested that the reoesaion Is\nteaching some employers the\ncoetllnaea of agreeing to sub\nstantial wage Increases far In\nadvance.\n\u201cIt la Mfe to my that the\nsteel Industry will long remem\nber the wage increases for 1958\nwhich it agreed to back In\n1956.\u201d Prof. Slichter Mid.\nStamp Honoring\nPaul Revere\nOut Tomorrow\nA new 25-cent ctamp mark\ning the 183 d annlverMry of\nPaul Revere s ride and bearing\nhis portrait will go on sale\nthroughout the country to- 1\nmorrow.\nBtamp enthusiasts in Boston,\nwhere Revere aroused the coun\ntryside In 1776. gat first crack\n|at the naw lasue. Over-the\ncounter Mies begin after cere\nmonies there today.\nAlert philatelists here, how\never. will have already Mnt\nself-addressed envelopes to the\nBoston postmaster, along with\n25 cents, and they will get them\nback bearing the prized \"first\nday of iasua\u201d cancellation.\nThe green stamp bears a re\nproduction of a Ollbert Stuart\nportrait of Revere, painted\nin 1813.\nPost office authorities pointed\nout the new stamp la not In the\nlimited-issue \u201ccommemorative\u201d\n\u2022oategory. but U part of the 1954\naeries and will continue to be\nprinted until the entire Series 4a\nrevised.\nCritic of Faubus\nQuits Little Rock\nLITTLE ROCK, Ark, April!\n19 (JP). Former Little Rock\nMayor Woodrow Wilson Mann\nIs moving to Denver. Colo, to\ntake a Job with a newly formed\nInvestment company.\nMr. Mann was an outspoken\ncritic of Oov. Orval Faubus\nduring the peak of the school\nIntegration controversy here\nlast year. More recently*he had\nbeen rumored as a possible\ncandidate for the Democratic\ngubernatorial nomination.\nMr. Mann Mid he had been\noffered a fine opportunity\u201d in\n\u2022Donver.\nHe has been in the insurance\nbusiness. He left office as\nMayor last November when the\nLittle Rock city government\nwas changed to the board-|i\nmanager type.\n.1\nFormer Policeman\nWins Theft Acquittal\nA 36-year-old former Capitol\npoliceman and part-time de\ntective for Hecht\u2019s Farktngton\nstore was acquitted yesterday\nIn Arlington County Court of\ncharges of stealing a radio\nfrom the store.\nThe former policeman. Albert\nJ. Salem of 706 North Wayne\nstreet. Arlington, has been held\nfor grand Jury action on a\ncharge of stealing a camera\nvalued at fill from the store.\nHe also faces a County Court\nhearing on three other petty\nlarceny charge* Involving\nradios on May 7.\nThe radio theft charge\nagainst Salem waa dismissed\nby Judge Paul D. Brown for\nlack of evidence. Salem told\nthe court he bought the radio\nlast fall.\nNavy Artists\nTo Hold Show\n\nThe Navy Bureau of Aero\nnautics Recreation Association;\nwill open its third annual arts!\nand crafts show at 4:30 p.m.\nSunday In the lobby of the\nMain Navy Building.\nExhibitors are military and\ncivilian employes of the bu\nreau In the Metropolitan Area.\nTha items on vitw include oils,\ndrswlngs, sketches and hand!-!\nwork such as ceramics, needle-'\nwork end Jewelry.\nI Capt. Barton E. Day, USN,\nIs chairman of the combined\narts and crafts show. Rear Ad\nmiral Robert E. Dixon, chief\n!of the Bureau of Aeronautics,\n\u2022will announce awards at Sun\nday\u2019s opening.\nMaurice Slegler. deputy di\nrector of arts at the University\nof Maryland, la Judge of the\nart In the ahow. Judges for the;\ncrafts are Oeorge King of\nKing's Interior* and Mischa\nSchreibman of the Connoisseur\nShop.\nThe exhibits will be open for\npublic viewing from 8 a.m. to\n4:30 p.m. week days from Mon\nday through May 2, The Main\nNavy Building Is at Eighteenth\nstreet and Constitution avenue\nN.W.\nTAKOMA\nFUNSRAL HOME\nJ. Arthur Walters, Owner\nMaude J. Walters\nWilliam S. Clark, Manager\n254 Carrol! St. N.W\nRAndolph 6-5200\nLarge parking facilities directly\nopposite Funeral Home\nL\nMAN ON GIRDER\n40 FEET IN AIR\nJUST DOING JOB\nNEW YORK\nconverged on Manhattan\nbridge yesterday and one\nof them climbed toward\nman perched 40 feet up on\ngirder.\nHalf way up. the police\nman persuaded the pereh\ner-ln-perll to corns down.\n\u201cWhy did you do It?\"\nthe police asked Edward J.\nHaggerty. 60.\nBecause it's my Job.\u201d he\nsnapped. \u201cI'm an inspector\nin the department of public\nworks and I have to look\nover tbe steel work every\nThursday.\"\nThe police went away\nand Mr. Haggerty climbed\nback up among the girders.\nStreetcar Bill\nCalls for Hearing\nPrior to Ban\nThe Public Utilities Commis\nsion would be required to hold\npublic hearings before approv\ning conversion of D. C. Transit\nSystem. Inc, to an all-bus op\neration. under a bill Introduced\nin the House yeeterday.\nSponsor of the measure Is\nRepresentative Lankford, Dem\nocrat of Maryland.\nMr. Lankford Mid he offered\nthe bill at the request of a\nnumber of citizens. HU own in\nterest in the situation centers\naround the streetcar line on\nRhode Island avenue NX serv\ning the Mt. Rainier. Hyatteville\nand College Park areas.\nUnder terms of the franchise\ngranted D. C. Transit on July\n24. 1966, It was to complete its\nconversion from streetcars to\nbuses within seven years, un\nless the utilities commission ex\ntends the time.\nMr. Lankford Mid he had\ndiscussed the measure with\nRepresentative McMillan. Dem\nocrat of South Carolina, chair\nman of tha House District\nCommittee, and had received\nhU Indorsement. Tbe bill toes\nto Mr. McMillan's committee,\nbut no action has been taken\non setting it down for public\nhearings.\nOff-Course Auto\nRuins Garaged Car\nMOUNT VERNON. Ohio (/PI.\nPolice Mid there were two\nthings wrong when Arthur Sun\nkel turned In a driveway here.\nFirat. he was 40 miles from his\nown garage in Wanaw, Ohio.\nSecond, he didn't stop.\nThey Mid Sunkel's car went\ninto the garage attached to the\nHugh McLaman home and\nknocked the McLarnan car\nthrough the back of the garage\nand off a 6-foot drop. Sunkel\nwas fined 650 In Municipal\nCourt for reckless driving.\nAdmiral to Transfer\nHr the Ate\u00abclet*2 Fret*\nRear Admiral W. A. Dolan.\nJr, commandant of the Pugst\nSound Naval Shipyard at Bre\nmerton. Wash, since 1955. will\nbe transferred here in June. He\nwill exchange positions with\nRear Admiral P. w. Snyder,\nnow an assistant chief of the\nBureau of Ships.\nMONTBOMIRT COUNTY\nHEART FUND\n10. 4-40*\n3744 Howord Av., Komington, Md\nGRATEFULLY\nACKNOWLEDGES GIFTS\nRECEIVED IN MEMORY OF\nMr*. Lao Divln\nGoor